 piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lucelle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Andre, Aurele, Benoit, Cecile, Marcel, Marie Paule.","Altered form of French <b>Laselle</b>: habitational name from La Selle, the name of several places in various parts of France. The surname <i>Laselle</i> is very rare in France, found in Marne. Compare   Lascelles  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Lacelle in Corrèze or numerous minor places called La Celle, all named for a monastic cell or hermitage in their vicinity, from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’."],"variants":[{"name":"Lascelles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from one of the large number of places in northern France called Celle, Celles, Lacelle, Leschelle, or Lachelle, all from French <i>celle</i> ‘hermitage’, and at different times occurring both with and without the plural <i>-s</i>.","Variant of   Lacelle   1, a surname of French origin."]}]},{"name":"Beatrice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and French form of   Beatrix  , which was quite popular in England during the Middle Ages, and strongly revived in the 19th century. It is most famous as the name of Dante's beloved, and is borne by the elder (  b. 1988 ) of the Duke of York's daughters."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrice de Lucelle was born in 1145, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Hugh de Lucelle, was 30 and her mother, Tilly, Lady of Calvados Basse, was 21. She had at least 3 sons with Richard de Gubion. She died after 1185, in Higham Gobion, Bedfordshire, England."},"et":{"1145–after 1185":"1145–pärast 1185","1145–1185":"1145–1185","1146–1182":"1146–1182","1165–1230":"1165–1230","–Male":"Surnud","1115–1159"